Delta State government has confirmed the receipt of N100 million from the federal government (FG), during the peak of the Coronavirus pandemic in the state. The state commissioner for Information, Mr Charles Aniagwu, made the disclosure yesterday, in Asaba, while briefing journalists about decisions of the state government on lockdown relaxation. He said the state has 1,780 confirmed cases of COVID-19, with over 1,600 discharged patients, leaving less than 180 active cases. According to him, the home care approach adopted by the state, yielded positive results, stating that the COVID-19 curve has come down compared to the earlier time. He revealed that individuals have also found out how to cope by way of taking some measures, while health givers also worked hard to fight the dreaded pandemic. Speaking further, Mr Aniagwu, said they are expected to fumigate their halls and observe all other COVID-19 protocols, warning that the use of facemasks is compulsory. While noting that the state would continue to monitor their activities, he said: “Necessary actions will be taken on anybody who contravenes the protocol.” On hotels, the state government said some of the eateries are now allowed for customers to eat: “But they must not permit buffet which allows everyone to use the same spoon to serve. We cannot guarantee that buffet will not increase the number of COVID-19,” adding that clubs and relaxation centres remain closed.